novel mutations","Stable equilibrium between mutation and selection","Selection for beneficial alleles","Maintenance of initial allele frequencies"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this small population, \u003Cstrong\u003Erandom fixation of one allele and loss of the other\u003C/strong\u003E is inevitable due to genetic drift. With only 20 birds, random chance in mating and reproduction will cause significant fluctuations in allele frequencies between generations. Eventually, one allele will likely reach 100% frequency while the other disappears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual distribution of novel mutations\u003C/strong\u003E would require a much larger population where random effects are minimal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStable equilibrium between mutation and selection\u003C/strong\u003E cannot occur because drift effects dominate in small populations\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelection for beneficial alleles\u003C/strong\u003E assumes natural selection is the primary force, but genetic drift acts independently of whether an allele is beneficial or harmful\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintenance of initial allele frequencies\u003C/strong\u003E is highly unlikely in small populations where random sampling effects are strong\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESince both alleles start at 50% frequency, each has an equal probability of becoming fixed in the population. The rate of fixation depends on population size - with only 20 birds, this process could occur relatively quickly over several generations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Genetic drift is random change in allele frequencies in a population due to chance sampling of gametes.","Genetic drift has strongest effects in small populations, potentially leading to loss of genetic diversity.","The probability of allele fixation through genetic drift depends on initial allele frequency and population size.","In small populations, genetic drift can override natural selection effects."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63626"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17268"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63626"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T21:22:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T21:30:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9958"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78217"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},